INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `title`, `author`, `category`, `photo`, `description`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1, 'their is no killing', '', '', '11903748_1004987299542789_7155652100225084026_n.jpg', 'Killing of BCL men in ‘gunfight’\r\nSpecial Correspondent | Update: 01:52, Aug 21, 2015 | Print Edition\r\n0 Like\r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n\r\nThe killing of three leaders of Bangladesh Chhatra League (BCL) in so-called gunfights has triggered unrest within the ruling Awami League.\r\n\r\nPanic has gripped the party’s rank and file. Some ruling party leaders including MPs have taken a stand against the law enforcers.\r\n\r\nAlthough some of the leaders extended support to the government’s “tough stance,” others are criticising the government’s position. They say killing party workers in the name of gunfight would not bring about any solution.\r\n\r\nProthom Alo has learnt that some of the party leaders voiced their grievances to the home minister, Asaduzzaman Khan Kamal, over phone.\r\n\r\nThe ruling party’s image was tarnished when a section of party leaders and workers resorted to killing, establishing their supremacy and criminal activities.\r\n\r\nThe government has taken a tough position against this backdrop.\r\n\r\nPrime minister Sheikh Hasina informed the last cabinet meeting that not an iota of lenience would be shown to criminals even if they belong to the party. \r\n\r\nShe ordered tough action against the criminals irrespective of their identity. \r\n\r\nThree BCL leaders were killed last Monday and Tuesday in the “gunfights” with the law enforcers. By doing so the government is giving a message to the ruling party leaders and workers across the country.\r\n\r\nMixed reaction was created in the AL leadership as panic has gripped the party’s rank and file.\r\n\r\nAL senior leader Suranjit Sengupta said, “Chhatra League is a political party formed with the ideals of Bangabandhu. They might have deviated, but crossfire is not a solution to that deviation. The solution will have to be made politically. We will have to find a solution by grooming party workers and leaders based on ideology and principles.”\r\n\r\nVenting his anger at the killing of BCL’s Hazaribagh thana unit president Arzu Mia in the so-called gunfight, local AL MP Sheikh Fazle Noor Taposh said Rapid Action Battalion (RAB) killed Arzu after picking him up, not in the gunfight.\r\n\r\nDwelling on the so-called gunfight, the MP said, “It is a so-called typical statement or claim. It does not make sense. It is not believable.”\r\n\r\nBesides, Hazaribagh AL and its front organisations lodged their protests at the killing of Arzu Mia by a organising press conference. The BCL has termed the killings an excess of the RAB, too.\r\n\r\nWhen contacted, BCL president Saifur Rahman said, “We support no killing. We will take action later after investigating the matter.”\r\n\r\nThe prime minister’s message to take a tough stance against criminal activities has already been sent to the heads of different law enforcement agencies.\r\n\r\nAbout BCL men’s resorting to criminal activities and internal conflicts, a senior minister said, “No one will go off scot-free after committing crimes. Action is being taken. The trend will fall shortly.”\r\n\r\nA senior AL leader said the party would not shoulder the responsibility of the crimes of a handful leaders and workers. “The party supports any steps of the government to improve law and order.”\r\n\r\nAL’s youth front Bangladesh Awami Jubo League’s general secretary Harunur Rashid said, “Our stance is zero tolerance to terrorism. The party expels anyone of the committee if found guilty.”   \r\n\r\nOver the last couple of days, several government ministers and AL leaders were making cautionary remarks against a section of party leaders and workers.\r\n\r\nAt a programme of Swechchhasebak League, AL general secretary Syed Ashraful Islam called on the party leaders and workers to give up greed. \r\n\r\nHe had said such a situation had cropped up before the killing of Sheikh Mujib, so as to kill him. He urged the party leaders and workers to remain careful so that such a situation does not recur.\r\n\r\nIn the same manner, health minister Mohammad Nasim and road transport and bridges minister Obaidul Quader also gave speeches warning the party workers and leaders.\r\n\r\nIncidents like killing of three party leaders in Badda over jhut business, killing of a party activist in a factional clash in Kushtia while observing the death anniversary of Sheikh Mujib, Juba League’s attacks on teachers and students in Chandpur demanding tolls and torturing Hazaribagh juvenile to death took place amidst the warnings from different senior ministers.\r\n\r\nBefore that, the incident of an unborn baby being shot in her mother’s womb in a factional clash of BCL in Magura drew huge flak from different quarters across the country.\r\n\r\nSeveral AL leaders while talking to Prothom Alo admitted that the absence of a visible political rival is dangerous and that is why the party is grappling to control its leaders and workers.\r\n\r\nThey said criminal activities of some of the party leaders and leaders are causing damage to the images of the party and of the government.\r\n\r\nBut they also said some of the party leaders are being involved in criminal activities for their personal interests. “They party leaders are trying to establish their supremacy in their locality in the wake of the possibility of local government elections early next year and that led to the factional clashes.”\r\n\r\nAL leader and food minister Quamrul Islam told BBC Thursday that the government has taken a policy of zero-tolerance to terrorism. “No matter what the political identity of the criminals is, the government’s target is to contain them with a firm fist. None will be spared and no concession will be made.”\r\n\r\nThe minister alleged the local party leaders of the respective areas are trying to protect themselves by terming the casualties in the gunfight with RAB extrajudicial killings.\r\n', 1440117481, 1440228605),
