INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `title`, `author`, `category`, `photo`, `description`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(11, ' Intelligence officials helped Maulana Tajuddin flee', '', '', '11903748_1004987299542789_7155652100225084026_n.jpg', '\r\n\r\nMaulana Tajuddin, who had allegedly supplied Arges grenades in the 21 August attack, is currently living in South Africa.\r\n\r\nThe government has taken steps to extradite Tajuddin, sources said.\r\n\r\nCertain officials of a powerful intelligence agency ensured Tajuddin safe passage abroad around nine years ago.\r\n\r\nLater, several reports published on the basis of intelligence sources, said Tajuddin was staying in South Africa with his brother Ratul Babu, another accused in the 21 August grenade attack.\r\n\r\nSouth Africa has agreed to send Tajuddin back to Bangladesh, home minister Asaduzzaman Khan said on Wednesday.\r\n\r\nThe decision came during a meeting between visiting South African delegation, led by Nomaindiya Mfeketo, deputy minister of the Department of International Relations and Cooperation of South Africa, and Bangladesh''s home minister at the latter''s secretariat office.\r\n\r\n"South Africa has agreed to send back Tajuddin and want to sign an extradition treaty with us. We have exchanged information and other documents for the next course of action,” state-run news agency Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha (BSS) quoted the home minister as saying.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, a secretary-level meeting between South Africa and Bangladesh was held at the ministry of foreign affairs in Dhaka on Thursday but the meeting did not raise the issue of Tajuddin’s extradition.\r\n\r\nTajuddin, who is a brother of Abdus Salam Pintu, a former deputy minister during the 2001-06 BNP-Jamaat coalition government, studied in Lahore, Pakistan.\r\n\r\nThe supplementary charge-sheet of the 21 August grenade case said Tajuddin had been involved with Kashmir-based terror group Lashkar-e-Taiba, Tehreek-e-Jihad-e-Islam, and Hizbul-Mujahideen.\r\n\r\nIt has been alleged that Tajuddin had close contacts with former state minister for home Lutfozzaman Babar.\r\n\r\nAccording to confessions of the accused and witnesses’ statements, Hizbul-Mujahideen leader Abdul Majid Bhatt alias Yousuf Bhatt, Muzaffar Shah of Tehreek-e-Jihad-e-Islam and Harkatul Jihad’s leader Mufti Hannan and Tajuddin landed in Bangladesh in 2003. They brought grenades and ammunition with them from Pakistan.\r\n\r\nMufti Hannan sent some of the grenades through his associates to India. The rest remained with Mufti Hannan and Tajuddin.\r\n\r\nThe investigation found that these grenades were used not just for the 21 August attack but for other incidents including attacks on former British high commissioner Anwar Chowdhury, Awami League leader Zebunnesa, and former finance minister Shah AMS Kibria.\r\n\r\nThe charge-sheet said Mufti Hannan’s associates Ahsan Ullah alias Kajol and Mufti Moin alias Jandal had met Tajuddin at Abdus Salam Pintu’s Dhanmondi residence on 20 August, the day before the gruesome attack on AL leaders at Gulistan. Tajuddin supplied them with 15 grenades which were used to conduct the 21 August attack that left at least 23 leaders and activists of the party killed and scores injured.\r\n\r\nMufti Hannan was arrested on 1 October, 2005 and then remanded for 120 days. During interrogations, Mufti Hannan informed intelligence officials about Tajuddin’s complicity in the attack.\r\n\r\nAccording to case documents, some Directorate General of Forces Intelligence (DGFI) officials provided a safe passage to Pakistan for Tajuddin on 10 October, 2006.\r\n\r\nFormer Major Monirul Islam said senior DGFI officials ensured a fake passport of Mohammad Badal, Pakistani visa, Dhaka-Karachi air ticket and airport entry for Tajuddin.\r\n\r\nThe supplementary charge-sheet said DGFI high-up Maj Gen ATM Amin, Lieutenant Colonel Saiful Islam Joarder and the prime minister’s private secretary at the time, Saiful Islam Duke, ensured Tajuddin safe passage to Pakistan.\r\n', 1440121405, 1440121405),
